      {
        "id": 2908533,
        "name": "William Kelley",
        "username": "William_Kelley",
        "avatar_template": "/user_avatar/www.wineberserkers.com/william_kelley/{size}/2314_2.png",
        "created_at": "2020-06-08T15:09:52.000Z",
        "cooked": "<p>3cm is a correct level for a 30-year-old wine, and from a cold cellar the 1990 Beaucastel is fully mature and drinking well. It\u2019s a softer, more open-knit wine than e.g. the 1989, and from a warm cellar or if it has traveled a lot, it might be on the gentle downslope. If it\u2019s the bottle listed on the site I think you\u2019re talking about, in so far as one can tell anything from the photos, it looks good.</p>\n<p>From the same site, the 1990 Les Cailloux from Andr\u00e9 Brunel is drinking well - it\u2019s a bit more muscular and alcoholic than the 1990 Beaucastel, but also a bit more vigorous at this stage. I would also consider the 1990 Guigal Hermitage, which is very good indeed.</p>",
